# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sparql-query
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:sparql-query/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] JSON-LD is based on the concept of a "context" that maps JSON object properties to concepts in an ontology using an RDF model.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] In order to map the JSON-LD syntax to RDF, JSON-LD allows values to be coerced to a specified type or tagged with a language.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] A context can be embedded directly in a JSON-LD document or put into a separate file and referenced from traditional JSON documents via an HTTP Link header.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] The example above describes a person, based on the FOAF (friend of a friend) ontology.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] First, the two JSON properties `name` and `homepage` and the type `Person` are mapped to concepts in the FOAF vocabulary and the value of the `homepage` property is specified to be of the type `@id`.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] In other words, the homepage id is specified to be an IRI in the context definition.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] Based on the RDF model, this allows the person described in the document to be unambiguously identified by an IRI.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] The use of resolvable IRIs allows RDF documents containing more information to be transcluded which enables clients to discover new data by following those links; this principle is known as 'Follow Your Nose'.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] By having all data semantically annotated as in the example, an RDF processor can identify that the document contains information about a person (`@type`) and if the processor understands the FOAF vocabulary it can determine which properties specify the person's name and homepage.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] The encoding is used by Schema.org, Google Knowledge Graph, and used mostly for search engine optimization activities.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] It has also been used for applications such as biomedical informatics, and representing provenance information.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] It is also the basis of Activity Streams, a format for "the exchange of information about potential and completed activities", and is used in ActivityPub, the federated social networking protocol.
[src:sparql-query/json-ld] Additionally, it is used in the context of Internet of Things (IoT), where a Thing Description, which is a JSON-LD document, describes the network facing interfaces of IoT devices.
[src:sparql-query/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:sparql-query/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:sparql-query/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:sparql-query/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:sparql-query/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The **Resource Description Framework** (**RDF**) is a method to describe and exchange graph data.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] It was originally designed as a data model for metadata by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] It provides a variety of syntax notations and formats, of which the most widely used is Turtle (Terse RDF Triple Language).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF is a directed graph composed of triple statements.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] An RDF graph statement is represented by: (1) a node for the subject, (2) an arc from subject to object, representing a predicate, and (3) a node for the object.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Each of these parts can be identified by a Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This simple, flexible data model has a lot of expressive power to represent complex situations, relationships, and other things of interest, while also being appropriately abstract.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF was adopted as a W3C recommendation in 1999.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The RDF 1.0 specification was published in 2004, and the RDF 1.1 specification in 2014.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SPARQL is a standard query language for RDF graphs.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF Schema (RDFS), Web Ontology Language (OWL) and SHACL (Shapes Constraint Language) are ontology languages that are used to describe RDF data.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The RDF data model is similar to classical conceptual modeling approaches (such as entity–relationship or class diagrams).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] It is based on the idea of making statements about resources (in particular web resources) in expressions of the form *subject*–*predicate*–*object*, known as *triples*.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The *subject* denotes the resource; the *predicate* denotes traits or aspects of the resource, and expresses a relationship between the *subject* and the *object*.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] For example, one way to represent the notion "The sky has the color blue" in RDF is as the triple: a subject denoting "the sky", a predicate denoting "has the color", and an object denoting "blue".
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Therefore, RDF uses *subject* instead of *object* (or *entity*) in contrast to the typical approach of an entity–attribute–value model in object-oriented design: entity (sky), attribute (color), and value (blue).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF is an abstract model with several serialization formats (being essentially specialized file formats).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In addition the particular encoding for resources or triples can vary from format to format.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF's simple data model and ability to model disparate, abstract concepts has also led to its increasing use in knowledge management applications unrelated to Semantic Web activity.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] A collection of RDF statements intrinsically represents a labeled, directed multigraph.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This makes an RDF data model better suited to certain kinds of knowledge representation than other relational or ontological models.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] As RDFS, OWL and SHACL demonstrate, one can build additional ontology languages upon RDF.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] A first public draft of RDF appeared in October 1997, issued by a W3C working group that included representatives from IBM, Microsoft, Netscape, Nokia, Reuters, SoftQuad, and the University of Michigan.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In 1999, the W3C published the first recommended RDF specification, the *Model and Syntax Specification* ("RDF M&S").
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This described RDF's data model and an XML serialization.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF saw little take-up in this period, but there was significant work done in Bristol, around ILRT at Bristol University and HP Labs, and in Boston at MIT.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RSS 1.0 and FOAF became exemplar applications for RDF in this period.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The recommendation of 1999 was replaced in 2004 by a set of six specifications: "The RDF Primer", "RDF Concepts and Abstract", "RDF/XML Syntax Specification (revised)", "RDF Semantics", "RDF Vocabulary Description Language 1.0", and "The RDF Test Cases".
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This series was superseded in 2014 by the following six "RDF 1.1" documents: "RDF 1.1 Primer", "RDF 1.1 Concepts and Abstract Syntax", "RDF 1.1 XML Syntax", "RDF 1.1 Semantics", "RDF Schema 1.1", and "RDF 1.1 Test Cases".
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] `rdf:Statement`, `rdf:subject`, `rdf:predicate`, `rdf:object` are used for reification (see below).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This vocabulary is used as a foundation for RDF Schema, where it is extended.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF/XML is sometimes misleadingly called simply RDF because it was introduced among the other W3C specifications defining RDF and it was historically the first W3C standard RDF serialization format.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] However, it is important to distinguish the RDF/XML format from the abstract RDF model itself.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Although the RDF/XML format is still in use, other RDF serializations are now preferred by many RDF users, both because they are more human-friendly, and because some RDF graphs are not representable in RDF/XML due to restrictions on the syntax of XML QNames.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] With a little effort, virtually any arbitrary XML may also be interpreted as RDF using GRDDL (pronounced 'griddle'), Gleaning Resource Descriptions from Dialects of Languages.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF triples may be stored in a type of database called a triplestore.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The subject of an RDF statement is either a uniform resource identifier (URI) or a blank node, both of which denote resources.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Resources indicated by blank nodes are called anonymous resources.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] They are not directly identifiable from the RDF statement.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The predicate is a URI which also indicates a resource, representing a relationship.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The object is a URI, blank node or a Unicode string literal.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] As of RDF 1.1 resources are identified by Internationalized Resource Identifiers (IRIs); IRIs are a generalization of URIs.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In Semantic Web applications, and in relatively popular applications of RDF like RSS and FOAF (Friend of a Friend), resources tend to be represented by URIs that intentionally denote, and can be used to access, actual data on the World Wide Web.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] But RDF, in general, is not limited to the description of Internet-based resources.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In fact, the URI that names a resource does not have to be dereferenceable at all.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] For example, a URI that begins with "http:" and is used as the subject of an RDF statement does not necessarily have to represent a resource that is accessible via HTTP, nor does it need to represent a tangible, network-accessible resource—such a URI could represent absolutely anything.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] However, there is broad agreement that a bare URI (without a # symbol) which returns a 300-level coded response when used in an HTTP GET request should be treated as denoting the internet resource that it succeeds in accessing.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Therefore, producers and consumers of RDF statements must agree on the semantics of resource identifiers.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Such agreement is not inherent to RDF itself, although there are some controlled vocabularies in common use, such as Dublin Core Metadata, which is partially mapped to a URI space for use in RDF.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The intent of publishing RDF-based ontologies on the Web is often to establish, or circumscribe, the intended meanings of the resource identifiers used to express data in RDF.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] is intended by its owners to refer to the class of all Merlot red wines by vintner (i.e., instances of the above URI each represent the class of all wine produced by a single vintner), a definition which is expressed by the OWL ontology—itself an RDF document—in which it occurs.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Without careful analysis of the definition, one might erroneously conclude that an instance of the above URI was something physical, instead of a type of wine.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Note that this is not a 'bare' resource identifier, but is rather a URI reference, containing the '#' character and ending with a fragment identifier.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Reification is sometimes important in order to deduce a level of confidence or degree of usefulness for each statement.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] More statements about the original statement may also exist, depending on the application's needs.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] For example, a statement can be associated with a context, named by a URI, in order to assert an "is true in" relationship.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] As another example, it is sometimes convenient to group statements by their source, which can be identified by a URI, such as the URI of a particular RDF/XML document.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Then, when updates are made to the source, corresponding statements can be changed in the model, as well.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Implementation of scopes does not necessarily require fully reified statements.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Some implementations allow a single scope identifier to be associated with a statement that has not been assigned a URI, itself.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Likewise *named graphs* in which a set of triples is named by a URI can represent context without the need to reify the triples.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The predominant query language for RDF graphs is SPARQL.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SPARQL is an SQL-like language, and a recommendation of the W3C as of January 15, 2008.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SHACL Advanced Features specification (W3C Working Group Note), the most recent version of which is maintained by the SHACL Community Group, defines support for SHACL Rules, used for data transformations, inferences and mappings of RDF based on SHACL shapes.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The predominant language for describing and validating RDF graphs is SHACL (Shapes Constraint Language).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SHACL specification is divided in two parts: SHACL Core and SHACL-SPARQL.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SHACL Core consists of a list of built-in constraints such as cardinality, range of values and many others.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] SHACL-SPARQL describes SPARQL-based constraints and an extension mechanism to declare new constraint components.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The resource "http://www.w3.org/People/EM/contact#me" is the subject.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In addition, the subject has a type (with URI http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type), which is person (with URI http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/pim/contact#Person).
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Certain concepts in RDF are taken from logic and linguistics, where subject-predicate and subject-predicate-object structures have meanings similar to, yet distinct from, the uses of those terms in RDF.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In the English language statement *'New York has the postal abbreviation NY'*,*'New York'* would be the subject, *'has the postal abbreviation'* the predicate and *'NY'* the object.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Encoded as an RDF triple, the subject and predicate would have to be resources named by URIs.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The object could be a resource or literal element.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] In this example, "urn:x-states:New%20York" is the URI for a resource that denotes the US state New York, "http://purl.org/dc/terms/alternative" is the URI for a predicate (whose human-readable definition can be found here), and "NY" is a literal string.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Note that the URIs chosen here are not standard, and do not need to be, as long as their meaning is known to whatever is reading them.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] However, RDF puts the information in a formal way that a machine can understand.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The purpose of RDF is to provide an encoding and interpretation mechanism so that resources can be described in a way that particular software can understand it; in other words, so that software can access and use information that it otherwise could not use.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Both versions of the statements above are wordy because one requirement for an RDF resource (as a subject or a predicate) is that it be unique.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The subject resource must be unique in an attempt to pinpoint the exact resource being described.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The predicate needs to be unique in order to reduce the chance that the idea of Title or Publisher will be ambiguous to software working with the description.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] If the software recognizes *http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title* (a specific definition for the concept of a title established by the Dublin Core Metadata Initiative), it will also know that this title is different from a land title or an honorary title or just the letters t-i-t-l-e put together.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] The following example, written in Turtle, shows how such simple claims can be elaborated on, by combining multiple RDF vocabularies.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Some uses of RDF include research into social networking.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] It will also help people in business fields understand better their relationships with members of industries that could be of use for product placement.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] It will also help scientists understand how people are connected to one another.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] RDF is being used to gain a better understanding of road traffic patterns.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This is because the information regarding traffic patterns is on different websites, and RDF is used to integrate information from different sources on the web.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Before, the common methodology was using keyword searching, but this method is problematic because it does not consider synonyms.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This is why ontologies are useful in this situation.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] But one of the issues that comes up when trying to efficiently study traffic is that to fully understand traffic, concepts related to people, streets, and roads must be well understood.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] Since these are human concepts, they require the addition of fuzzy logic.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This is because values that are useful when describing roads, like slipperiness, are not precise concepts and cannot be measured.
[src:sparql-query/resource-description-framework] This would imply that the best solution would incorporate both fuzzy logic and ontology.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The **Semantic Web**, sometimes known as **Web 3.0**, is an extension of the World Wide Web through standards set by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The goal of the Semantic Web is to make Internet data machine-readable.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] To enable the encoding of semantics with the data, technologies such as Resource Description Framework (RDF) and Web Ontology Language (OWL) are used.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] These technologies are used to formally represent metadata.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] For example, ontology can describe concepts, relationships between entities, and categories of things.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] These embedded semantics offer significant advantages such as reasoning over data and operating with heterogeneous data sources.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] These standards promote common data formats and exchange protocols on the Web, fundamentally the RDF.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] According to the W3C, "The Semantic Web provides a common framework that allows data to be shared and reused across application, enterprise, and community boundaries." The Semantic Web is therefore regarded as an integrator across different content and information applications and systems.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The term was coined by Tim Berners-Lee for a web of data (or **data web**) that can be processed by machines—that is, one in which much of the meaning is machine-readable.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] While its critics have questioned its feasibility, proponents argue that applications in library and information science, industry, biology and human sciences research have already proven the validity of the original concept.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The idea of adding semantics to the Web predates the term itself.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Berners-Lee discussed the need for semantics in the Web at the first International World Wide Web Conference in 1994.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In 1998, he published a design document titled "Semantic Web Road map", outlining the architecture for a web of machine-processable data.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The first patent for the creation of a semantic web was filed by Amit Sheth et al. on 30 October 2001.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The 2001 *Scientific American* article by Berners-Lee, Hendler, and Lassila described an expected evolution of the existing Web to a Semantic Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In 2006, Berners-Lee and colleagues stated that: "This simple idea…remains largely unrealized".
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In 2013, more than four million Web domains (out of roughly 250 million total) contained Semantic Web markup.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In the following example, the text "Paul Schuster was born in Dresden" on a website will be annotated, connecting a person with their place of birth.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The example defines the following five triples (shown in Turtle syntax).
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The triples result in the graph shown in the given figure.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] One of the advantages of using Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) is that they can be dereferenced using the HTTP protocol.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] According to the so-called Linked Open Data principles, such a dereferenced URI should result in a document that offers further data about the given URI.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In this example, all URIs, both for edges and nodes (e.g.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] `http://schema.org/Person`, `http://schema.org/birthPlace`, `http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1731`) can be dereferenced and will result in further RDF graphs, describing the URI, e.g. that Dresden is a city in Germany, or that a person, in the sense of that URI, can be fictional.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The second graph shows the previous example, but now enriched with a few of the triples from the documents that result from dereferencing `https://schema.org/Person` (green edge) and `https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1731` (blue edges).
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The concept of the semantic network model was formed in the early 1960s by researchers such as the cognitive scientist Allan M.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Collins, linguist Ross Quillian and psychologist Elizabeth F.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Loftus as a form to represent semantically structured knowledge.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] When applied in the context of the modern internet, it extends the network of hyperlinked human-readable web pages by inserting machine-readable metadata about pages and how they are related to each other.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] This enables automated agents to access the Web more intelligently and perform more tasks on behalf of users.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The term "Semantic Web" was coined by Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web and director of the World Wide Web Consortium ("W3C"), which oversees the development of proposed Semantic Web standards.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] He defines the Semantic Web as "a web of data that can be processed directly and indirectly by machines".
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Many of the technologies proposed by the W3C already existed before they were positioned under the W3C umbrella.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] These are used in various contexts, particularly those dealing with information that encompasses a limited and defined domain, and where sharing data is a common necessity, such as scientific research or data exchange among businesses.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In addition, other technologies with similar goals have emerged, such as microformats.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Many files on a typical computer can be loosely divided into either human-readable documents, or machine-readable data.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Examples of human-readable document files are mail messages, reports, and brochures.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Examples of machine-readable data files are calendars, address books, playlists, and spreadsheets, which are presented to a user using an application program that lets the files be viewed, searched, and combined.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Currently, the World Wide Web is based mainly on documents written in Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), a markup convention that is used for coding a body of text interspersed with multimedia objects such as images and interactive forms.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Metadata tags provide a method by which computers can categorize the content of web pages.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In the examples below, the field names "keywords", "description" and "author" are assigned values such as "computing", and "cheap widgets for sale" and "John Doe".
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Because of this metadata tagging and categorization, other computer systems that want to access and share this data can easily identify the relevant values.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] With HTML and a tool to render it (perhaps web browser software, perhaps another user agent), one can create and present a page that lists items for sale.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Rather, HTML can only say that the span of text "X586172" is something that should be positioned near "Acme Gizmo" and "€199", etc.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] There is no way to say "this is a catalog" or even to establish that "Acme Gizmo" is a kind of title or that "€199" is a price.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] There is also no way to express that these pieces of information are bound together in describing a discrete item, distinct from other items perhaps listed on the page.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Semantic HTML refers to the traditional HTML practice of markup following intention, rather than specifying layout details directly.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] For example, the use of `<em>` denoting "emphasis" rather than `<i>`, which specifies italics.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Layout details are left up to the browser, in combination with Cascading Style Sheets.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] But this practice falls short of specifying the semantics of objects such as items for sale or prices.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Microformats extend HTML syntax to create machine-readable semantic markup about objects including people, organizations, events and products.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Similar initiatives include RDFa, Microdata and Schema.org.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The Semantic Web takes the solution further.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] It involves publishing in languages specifically designed for data: Resource Description Framework (RDF), Web Ontology Language (OWL), and Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] HTML describes documents and the links between them.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] RDF, OWL, and XML, by contrast, can describe arbitrary things such as people, meetings, or airplane parts.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] These technologies are combined in order to provide descriptions that supplement or replace the content of Web documents.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Thus, content may manifest itself as descriptive data stored in Web-accessible databases, or as markup within documents (particularly, in Extensible HTML (XHTML) interspersed with XML, or, more often, purely in XML, with layout or rendering cues stored separately).
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The machine-readable descriptions enable content managers to add meaning to the content, i.e., to describe the structure of the knowledge we have about that content.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In this way, a machine can process knowledge itself, instead of text, using processes similar to human deductive reasoning and inference, thereby obtaining more meaningful results and helping computers to perform automated information gathering and research.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Tim Berners-Lee calls the resulting network of Linked Data the Giant Global Graph, in contrast to the HTML-based World Wide Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Berners-Lee posits that if the past was document sharing, the future is data sharing.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] His answer to the question of "how" provides three points of instruction.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Two, anyone accessing the URL should get data back.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Three, relationships in the data should point to additional URLs with data.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Tags, including hierarchical categories and tags that are collaboratively added and maintained (e.g. with folksonomies) can be considered part of, of potential use to or a step towards the semantic Web vision.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Unique identifiers, including hierarchical categories and collaboratively added ones, analysis tools and metadata, including tags, can be used to create forms of semantic webs – webs that are to a certain degree semantic.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In particular, such has been used for structuring scientific research i.a. by research topics and scientific fields by the projects OpenAlex, Wikidata and Scholia which are under development and provide APIs, Web-pages, feeds and graphs for various semantic queries.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Tim Berners-Lee has described the Semantic Web as a component of Web 3.0.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] "Semantic Web" is sometimes used as a synonym for "Web 3.0", though the definition of each term varies.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The next generation of the Web is often termed Web 4.0, but its definition is not clear.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] According to some sources, it is a Web that involves artificial intelligence, the internet of things, pervasive computing, ubiquitous computing and the Web of Things among other concepts.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] According to the European Union, Web 4.0 is "the expected fourth generation of the World Wide Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Some of the challenges for the Semantic Web include vastness, vagueness, uncertainty, inconsistency, and deceit.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Automated reasoning systems will have to deal with all of these issues in order to deliver on the promise of the Semantic Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] This list of challenges is illustrative rather than exhaustive, and it focuses on the challenges to the "unifying logic" and "proof" layers of the Semantic Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Incubator Group for Uncertainty Reasoning for the World Wide Web (URW3-XG) final report lumps these problems together under the single heading of "uncertainty".
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Many of the techniques mentioned here will require extensions to the Web Ontology Language (OWL) for example to annotate conditional probabilities.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Standardization for Semantic Web in the context of Web 3.0 is under the care of W3C.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The term "Semantic Web" is often used more specifically to refer to the formats and technologies that enable it.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The collection, structuring and recovery of linked data are enabled by technologies that provide a formal description of concepts, terms, and relationships within a given knowledge domain.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The Semantic Web Stack illustrates the architecture of the Semantic Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Such services could be useful to public search engines, or could be used for knowledge management within an organization.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In a corporation, there is a closed group of users and the management is able to enforce company guidelines like the adoption of specific ontologies and use of semantic annotation.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Compared to the public Semantic Web there are lesser requirements on scalability and the information circulating within a company can be more trusted in general; privacy is less of an issue outside of handling of customer data.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Critics question the basic feasibility of a complete or even partial fulfillment of the Semantic Web, pointing out both difficulties in setting it up and a lack of general-purpose usefulness that prevents the required effort from being invested.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] According to Marshall and Shipman, the tacit and changing nature of much knowledge adds to the knowledge engineering problem, and limits the Semantic Web's applicability to specific domains.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] A further issue that they point out are domain- or organization-specific ways to express knowledge, which must be solved through community agreement rather than only technical means.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] As it turns out, specialized communities and organizations for intra-company projects have tended to adopt semantic web technologies greater than peripheral and less-specialized communities.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The practical constraints toward adoption have appeared less challenging where domain and scope is more limited than that of the general public and the World-Wide Web.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Cory Doctorow's critique ("metacrap") is from the perspective of human behavior and personal preferences.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] For example, people may include spurious metadata into Web pages in an attempt to mislead Semantic Web engines that naively assume the metadata's veracity.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] This phenomenon was well known with metatags that fooled the Altavista ranking algorithm into elevating the ranking of certain Web pages: the Google indexing engine specifically looks for such attempts at manipulation.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Peter Gärdenfors and Timo Honkela point out that logic-based semantic web technologies cover only a fraction of the relevant phenomena related to semantics.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Enthusiasm about the semantic web could be tempered by concerns regarding censorship and privacy.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] For instance, text-analyzing techniques can now be easily bypassed by using other words, metaphors for instance, or by using images in place of words.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] An advanced implementation of the semantic web would make it much easier for governments to control the viewing and creation of online information, as this information would be much easier for an automated content-blocking machine to understand.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] In addition, the issue has also been raised that, with the use of FOAF files and geolocation meta-data, there would be very little anonymity associated with the authorship of articles on things such as a personal blog.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Some of these concerns were addressed in the "Policy Aware Web" project and is an active research and development topic.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Another criticism of the semantic web is that it would be much more time-consuming to create and publish content because there would need to be two formats for one piece of data: one for human viewing and one for machines.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] However, many web applications in development are addressing this issue by creating a machine-readable format upon the publishing of data or the request of a machine for such data.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The development of microformats has been one reaction to this kind of criticism.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Another argument in defense of the feasibility of semantic web is the likely falling price of human intelligence tasks in digital labor markets, such as Amazon's Mechanical Turk.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Specifications such as eRDF and RDFa allow arbitrary RDF data to be embedded in HTML pages.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The GRDDL (Gleaning Resource Descriptions from Dialects of Language) mechanism allows existing material (including microformats) to be automatically interpreted as RDF, so publishers only need to use a single format, such as HTML.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The first research group explicitly focusing on the Corporate Semantic Web was the ACACIA team at INRIA-Sophia-Antipolis, founded in 2002.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Results of their work include the RDF(S) based Corese search engine, and the application of semantic web technology in the realm of distributed artificial intelligence for knowledge management (e.g. ontologies and multi-agent systems for corporate semantic Web) and E-learning.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Since 2008, the Corporate Semantic Web research group, located at the Free University of Berlin, focuses on building blocks: Corporate Semantic Search, Corporate Semantic Collaboration, and Corporate Ontology Engineering.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Ontology engineering research includes the question of how to involve non-expert users in creating ontologies and semantically annotated content and for extracting explicit knowledge from the interaction of users within enterprises.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] Tim O'Reilly, who coined the term Web 2.0, proposed a long-term vision of the Semantic Web as a web of data, where sophisticated applications are navigating and manipulating it.
[src:sparql-query/semantic-web] The data web transforms the World Wide Web from a distributed file system into a distributed database.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] SPARQL allows for a query to consist of triple patterns, conjunctions, disjunctions, and optional patterns.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Implementations for multiple programming languages exist.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] There exist tools that allow one to connect and semi-automatically construct a SPARQL query for a SPARQL endpoint, for example ViziQuer.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] In addition, tools exist to translate SPARQL queries to other query languages, for example to SQL and to XQuery.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] SPARQL allows users to write queries that follow the RDF specification of the W3C.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Thus, the entire dataset is "subject-predicate-object" triples.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Subjects and predicates are always URI identifiers, but objects can be URIs or literal values.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] This single physical schema of three "columns" is hypernormalized in that what would be one relational record with (for example) four columns is now four triples with the subject being repeated over and over, the predicate essentially being the column name, and the object being the column value.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] In SPARQL, the first time a variable is encountered in the expression pipeline, it is populated with result.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The second and subsequent times it is seen, it is used as an input.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] But with a simple switch of the binding variable, the behavior is reversed.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Bound variables can therefore also be lists and will be operated upon without complicated syntax.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Unlike SQL which has subqueries and CTEs, SPARQL is much more like MongoDB or SPARK.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Expressions are evaluated exactly in the order they are declared including filtering and joining of data.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The programming model becomes what a SQL statement would be like with multiple WHERE clauses.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The combination of list-aware subjects and objects plus a pipeline approach can yield extremely expressive queries spanning many different domains of data.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] JOIN as used in RDBMS and understanding the dynamics of the JOIN (e.g. what column in what table is suitable to join to another, inner vs. outer, etc.) is not relevant in SPARQL (and in some ways simpler) because objects, if an URI and not a literal, implicitly can be used *only* to find a subject.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Here is a more comprehensive example that illustrates the pipeline using some syntax shortcuts.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Unlike relational databases, the object column is heterogeneous: the object data type, if not an URI, is usually implied (or specified in the ontology) by the predicate value.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Literal nodes carry type information consistent with the underlying XSD namespace including signed and unsigned short and long integers, single and double precision floats, datetime, penny-precise decimal, Boolean, and string.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Triple store implementations on traditional relational databases will typically store the value as a string and a fourth column will identify the real type.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Polymorphic databases such as MongoDB and SQLite can store the native value directly into the object field.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Thus, SPARQL provides a full set of analytic query operations such as `JOIN`, `SORT`, `AGGREGATE` for data whose schema is intrinsically part of the data rather than requiring a separate schema definition.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] However, schema information (the ontology) is often provided externally, to allow joining of different datasets unambiguously.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] In addition, SPARQL provides specific graph traversal syntax for data that can be thought of as a graph.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The example below demonstrates a simple query that leverages the ontology definition `foaf` ("friend of a friend").
[src:sparql-query/sparql] This query joins all of the triples with a matching subject, where the type predicate, "`a`", is a person (`foaf:Person`), and the person has one or more names (`foaf:name`) and mailboxes (`foaf:mbox`).
[src:sparql-query/sparql] For the sake of readability, the author of this query chose to reference the subject using the variable name "`?person`".
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Since the first element of the triple is always the subject, the author could have just as easily used any variable name, such as "`?subj`" or "`?x`".
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Whatever name is chosen, it must be the same on each line of the query to signify that the query engine is to join triples with the same subject.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The result of the join is a set of rows – `?person`, `?name`, `?email`.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] This query returns the `?name` and `?email` because `?person` is often a complex URI rather than a human-friendly string.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Note that any `?person` may have multiple mailboxes, so in the returned set, a `?name` row may appear multiple times, once for each mailbox, duplicating the `?name`.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] An important consideration in SPARQL is that when lookup conditions are not met in the pipeline for terminal entities like `?email`, then the *whole row is excluded*, unlike SQL where typically a null column is returned.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The query above will return only those `?person` where both at least one `?name` and at least one `?email` can be found.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] If a `?person` had no email, they would be excluded.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] This query can be distributed to multiple SPARQL endpoints (services that accept SPARQL queries and return results), computed, and results gathered, a procedure known as federated query.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Whether in a federated manner or locally, additional triple definitions in the query could allow joins to different subject types, such as automobiles, to allow simple queries, for example, to return a list of names and emails for people who drive automobiles with a high fuel efficiency.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] In the case of queries that read data from the database, the SPARQL language specifies four different query variations for different purposes.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Used to extract raw values from a SPARQL endpoint, the results are returned in a table format.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Used to extract information from the SPARQL endpoint and transform the results into valid RDF.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Used to provide a simple True/False result for a query on a SPARQL endpoint.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Used to extract an RDF graph from the SPARQL endpoint, the content of which is left to the endpoint to decide, based on what the maintainer deems as useful information.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Each of these query forms takes a `WHERE` block to restrict the query, although, in the case of the `DESCRIBE` query, the `WHERE` is optional.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] SPARQL 1.1 specifies a language for updating the database with several new query forms.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Variables are indicated by a `?` or `$` prefix.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Bindings for `?capital` and the `?country` will be returned.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] When a triple ends with a semicolon, the subject from this triple will implicitly complete the following pair to an entire triple.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] So for example `ex:isCapitalOf ?y` is short for `?x ex:isCapitalOf ?y`.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] The SPARQL query processor will search for sets of triples that match these four triple patterns, binding the variables in the query to the corresponding parts of each triple.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] Important to note here is the "property orientation" (class matches can be conducted solely through class-attributes or properties – see Duck typing).
[src:sparql-query/sparql] To make queries concise, SPARQL allows the definition of prefixes and base URIs in a fashion similar to Turtle.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] In this query, the prefix "`ex`" stands for “`http://example.com/exampleOntology#`”.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] SPARQL has native dateTime operations as well.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] GeoSPARQL defines filter functions for geographic information system (GIS) queries using well-understood OGC standards (GML, WKT, etc.).
[src:sparql-query/sparql] It enables the RDF store to be updated with this declarative query language, by adding `INSERT` and `DELETE` methods.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] XSPARQL is an integrated query language combining XQuery with SPARQL to query both XML and RDF data sources at once.
[src:sparql-query/sparql] See List of SPARQL implementations for more comprehensive coverage, including triplestore, APIs, and other storages that have implemented the SPARQL standard.
